In [3]:
import os
import requests

# Define the URL
#the format as "json" at the end of the URL used to resolve the "InvalidSchema" error. 
csv_url = "https://api.tidesandcurrents.noaa.gov/api/prod/datagetter?product=water_level&application=NOS.COOPS.TAC.WL&begin_date=20230824&end_date=20230825&datum=MLLW&station=9443090&time_zone=GMT&units=english&format=json"

# Specify the output directory and filename
output_directory = "C:\\Users\\cbeau\\OneDrive - UNC-Wilmington\\Documents" 
output_filename = "Beaulieu_Carter_HW2"

# Set the full path to the output file
output_filepath = os.path.join(output_directory, output_filename)

# Download the CSV file
response = requests.get(csv_url)

# Check if the request was successful
if response.status_code == 200:
    # Save the content to a local file
    with open(output_filepath, "wb") as file:
        file.write(response.content)
    print(f"File downloaded to: {output_filepath}")
else:
    print(f"Error: Unable to download file. Status code: {response.status_code}")

import pandas as pd

# Define the path to your file
#Need double backslashes
Neah_Bay_Water_Levels= "C:\\Users\\cbeau\\Downloads\\CO-OPS__9443090__wl (1).csv"

# Read the file into a Pandas DataFrame
data = pd.read_csv(Neah_Bay_Water_Levels)
print(data.columns)


#Convert the 'time' column to 'datenum' format (assuming it's in a datetime-like format)
data['Date Time'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Date Time']).apply(lambda x: x.timestamp()) 

#Extract the desired columns into separate arrays
time = data['Date Time']
WaterLevel = data[' Water Level'] #Water Level column and Sigma column have space in front as denoted in printed data columns
WaterSigma = data[' Sigma']

Index(['Date Time', ' Water Level', ' Sigma', ' O or I (for verified)', ' F',
       ' R', ' L', ' Quality '],
      dtype='object')
In [5]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from scipy.stats import skew


# Calculate the sample mean (η̄)
wlmean= data[' Water Level'].mean()

# Calculate the standard deviation (s)
wlstd= data[' Water Level'].std()

# Calculate the skewness (γ)
wlskewness= skew(data[' Water Level'])

print(f"Water Level Sample Mean (η̄): {wlmean}")
print(f"Water Level Standard Deviation (s): {wlstd}")
print(f"Water Level Skewness (γ): {wlskewness}")

#or assuming sigma column represents sd to find the mean could add/subtract sigma column to water level column

# Calculate the sample mean (η̄)
smean= data[' Sigma'].mean()

# Calculate the standard deviation (s)
sstd= data[' Sigma'].std()

# Calculate the skewness (γ)
sskewness= skew(data[' Sigma'])

print(f"Sigma Sample Mean (η̄): {smean}")
print(f"Sigma Standard Deviation (s): {sstd}")
print(f"Sigma Skewness (γ): {sskewness}")

Water Level Sample Mean (η̄): 3.9675627604166666
Water Level Standard Deviation (s): 2.3882384461905537
Water Level Skewness (γ): -0.3947463937243845
Sigma Sample Mean (η̄): 0.033555859375000004
Sigma Standard Deviation (s): 0.01597249897713113
Sigma Skewness (γ): 0.5449694184418451
In [6]:
#To estimate the uncertainty of each 6-minute mean (η̄i) using the provided standard deviation (σi) time series, you can use the standard error formula.
#SE(η̄i) = σi / √n
#SE(η̄i) is the standard error of the 6-minute mean η̄i.
#σi is the standard deviation of the raw 1-minute interval measurements for the corresponding 6-minute mean.
#n is the number of data points used to calculate each 6-minute mean.
data['Standard Error'] = data[' Sigma'] / np.sqrt(6) 

# The 'Standard Error' column now contains the uncertainty (SE) for each 6-minute mean

# You can also calculate the confidence interval for each 6-minute mean
# For a 95% confidence interval, you can use the formula:
# CI(η̄i) = ±1.96 * SE(η̄i)

data['95% CI Lower'] = data[' Water Level'] - 1.96 * data['Standard Error']  # Replace 'Water_Level' with your actual column name
data['95% CI Upper'] = data[' Water Level'] + 1.96 * data['Standard Error']  # Replace 'Water_Level' with your actual column name

# The '95% CI Lower' and '95% CI Upper' columns now contain the confidence interval bounds for each 6-minute mean

# Print the standard errors for each 6-minute mean
for se in data['Standard Error']:
    print(f"Standard Error: {se}")

# Print the DataFrame with the added columns
print(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt


# Create a figure and the first subplot (for η(t))
fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))

# Plot η(t) on the first axis
ax1.plot(data['Date Time'], data[' Water Level'], label='Water Level', color='blue')
ax1.set_xlabel('Time')
ax1.set_ylabel('Water Level (feet)', color='blue') 
ax1.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='blue')
ax1.legend(loc='upper left')

# Create a second y-axis on the right side of the plot
ax2 = ax1.twinx()

# Plot uncertainty on the second axis
ax2.plot(data['Date Time'], data['Standard Error'], label='Standard Error', color='red')
ax2.set_ylabel('Standard Error (feet)', color='red')  # Replace 'units' with the actual unit of measurement
ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='red')
ax2.legend(loc='upper right')

# Add a title and figure caption
plt.title('Water Level Record η(t) and Uncertainty')
plt.figtext(0.5, 0.02, 'Time', ha='center')
plt.figtext(0.5, 0.95, 'Water Level Record and Uncertainty', ha='center', fontsize=14)

# Show the plot
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming you have a DataFrame 'data' with columns 'Date Time', 'Water Level', and 'Standard Error'

# Create a figure and two subplots (one for η(t) and one for uncertainty)
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(10, 8), sharex=True)

# Plot η(t)
ax1.plot(data['Date Time'], data[' Water Level'], label='Water Level', color='blue')
ax1.set_ylabel('Water Level (feet)')  # Replace 'units' with the actual unit of measurement
ax1.legend()

# Plot uncertainty
ax2.plot(data['Date Time'], data['Standard Error'], label='Standard Error', color='red')
ax2.set_xlabel('Time')
ax2.set_ylabel('Standard Error (feet)')  # Replace 'units' with the actual unit of measurement
ax2.legend()

# Add a figure caption
fig.text(0.5, 0.02, 'Time', ha='center')
fig.text(0.5, 0.94, 'Water Level Record and Uncertainty', ha='center', fontsize=14)
fig.suptitle('Water Level Record η(t) and Uncertainty', fontsize=16)

# Show the plot
plt.show()
In [29]:
#To calculate the relative magnitude of uncertainty to the tidal amplitude, you can use the following formula:
#Relative Uncertainty = (Uncertainty / Tidal Amplitude) * 100
#Where:"Relative Uncertainty"- is the relative magnitude of uncertainty as a percentage."Uncertainty"- represents the margin of error or uncertainty associated with the tidal amplitude measurement or prediction.
#"Tidal Amplitude"-is the magnitude of the tidal range, typically measured as the difference between the high tide and low tide water levels.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

# Example tidal data as a list of water levels (in feet) over a time period
tidal_data = data[' Water Level']
# Uncertainty data as a list of standard error (in feet) over a time period
uncertainty = data['Standard Error']

# Initialize variables
cycle_start = 0  # Initialize the start index of the cycle
tidal_amplitudes = []
relative_uncertainties = []

# Loop through the data to calculate tidal amplitudes and relative uncertainties
for i in range(1, len(tidal_data)):
    if tidal_data[i] < tidal_data[i - 1]:
        # End of a cycle; calculate tidal amplitude and relative uncertainty
        max_level = max(tidal_data[cycle_start:i])
        min_level = min(tidal_data[cycle_start:i])
        tidal_amplitude = max_level - min_level
        
        if tidal_amplitude == 0:
            relative_uncertainty = np.nan  # Handle zero tidal amplitude by setting relative uncertainty to NaN
        else:
            relative_uncertainty = (uncertainty[i] / tidal_amplitude) * 100  # Calculate relative uncertainty for this data point
        
        tidal_amplitudes.append(tidal_amplitude)
        relative_uncertainties.append(relative_uncertainty)
        cycle_start = i  # Update the start index for the next cycle

# Filter out NaN values based on indices in both lists
filtered_tidal_amplitudes = [tidal_amplitudes[i] for i in range(len(relative_uncertainties)) if not np.isnan(relative_uncertainties[i])]
filtered_relative_uncertainties = [r for r in relative_uncertainties if not np.isnan(r)]

# Plot the relative uncertainty vs. tidal amplitude, ignoring NaN values
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(filtered_tidal_amplitudes, filtered_relative_uncertainties, c='blue', marker='o', alpha=0.7)
plt.xlabel('Tidal Amplitude (feet)')
plt.ylabel('Relative Uncertainty (%)')
plt.title('Relative Uncertainty vs. Tidal Amplitude')
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

plt.show()
